<paragraph blockId="46.[151,1436,474,931]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,326,726,751]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Leaf mine.</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[342,437,726,751]" captionStart="FIGURES 133–143" captionStartId="115.[151,264,1660,1683]" captionTargetBox="[151,1437,193,1639]" captionTargetId="figure@115.[151,1437,193,1639]" captionTargetPageId="115" captionText="FIGURES 133–143. leaf mines; 133: Liriomyza arctii Spencer in Ƒerbesina alternifolia; 134: L. asclepiadis Spencer in Asclepias exaltata; 135: L. baccharidis Spencer in Erigeron annuus, lower surface (left) and upper surface (right); 136: L. blechi Spencer in Plantago virginica; 137: L. brassicae (Riley) in Lepidium virginicum; 138: L. eupatoriella Spencer in Ageratina altissima; 139: L. eupatoriella in Ƒernonia baldwinii; 140: L. eupatorii (Kaltenbach) in Baccharis halimifolia; 141: L. fricki Spencer in Trifolium repens; 142: L. galiivora (Spencer) in Galium circaezans (transmitted light); 143: L. ivorcutleri spec. nov. in Silphium perfoliatum." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1452947/files/figure.png" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Fig. 135</figureCitation>
) According to 
<bibRefCitation box="[607,781,727,751]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" refId="ref103345" refString="Spencer, K. A. (1981) A revisionary study of the leaf-mining flies (Agromyzidae) of California. University of California Division of Agricultural Sciences Special Publication, 3273, 1 - 489." type="journal article">Spencer (1981)</bibRefCitation>
, a “dark, upper surface linear mine which not infrequently starts at the apex of a leaf and there appears blotch-like”; frass is in black strips. The mines on 
<emphasis box="[1246,1436,764,787]" italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">
Erigeron 
<taxonomicName box="[1355,1436,764,787]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Helianthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="annuus">annuus</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
were whitish and entirely linear, 
<quantity box="[523,618,799,823]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" metricValueMax="2.0" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" unit="mm" value="1.5" valueMax="2.0" valueMin="1.0">1–2 mm</quantity>
wide at the end, at least some of them switching between the upper and lower leaf surfaces.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
